OPMA02852 Nobuhiro Koyama1,2 ● Satoru Shigeno1,2 ● Akihiko Kanamoto3 ● Hiroshi Tomoda1,2 Received: 6 December 2019 / Revised: 21 January 2020 / Accepted: 6 February 2020 © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to the Japan Antibiotics Research Association 2020 Abstract The marine actinomycete strain OPMA02852, identiﬁed as the genus Streptomyces, was found to produce anti-mycobacterial compounds against Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC). One new compound, designated as stefﬁmycin E (1), was isolated together with three known stefﬁmycins (stefﬁmycin (2), 10-dihydrostefﬁmycin (3), and 8-demethoxystefﬁmycin (4)) from the culture broth of this producing microorganism by solvent extraction, ODS column chromatography, and preparative HPLC. Compound 1 has a tetracyclic quinone structure with a sugar moiety. Compound 1 exhibited anti-mycobacterial activity against M. intracellulare, M. bovis BCG, and M. smegmatis.

Mycobacterium avium complex (MAC) is a serious disease caused by common bacteria such as M. avium and M. intracellulare. In recent years, the number of patients infec- ted with MAC has increased to greater than that with tuberculosis [1, 2]. Although antibacterial drugs, including clarithromycin (CAM), ethambutol, and rifampicin, are cur- rently used to treat MAC infection, their therapeutic effects are limited. The development of new drugs that are effective against MAC infection is strongly desired. Based on this background, we focused on the discovery of new compounds Dedicated to Professor William Fenical in recognition of his contributions to marine-derived secondary metabolites. In the course of this screening program of microbial origins, a new compound named stefﬁmycin E (1) was isolated toge- ther with three known and structurally related compounds, stefﬁmycin [3] (2), 10-dihydrostefﬁmycin [4] (3), and 8- demethoxystefﬁmycin [5] (4), from the culture broth of Streptomyces sp. OPMA02852 (Fig. 1). The isolation, structural elucidation, and biological activity of 1 are described herein. The culture broth of Streptomyces sp. OPMA02852 (3.0 L) was extracted with an equal volume of ethyl acetate. The ethyl acetate fraction was separated by suction ﬁltration and concentrated in vacuo to yield a red crude extract (114 mg). The crude extract was dissolved in a small volume of methanol, applied to an ODS column (YMC GEL ODS-A, 5.5 g, i.d. 10 × 150 mm), and eluted stepwise with 0, 20, 40, 60, 80, and 100% aq CH3CN (30 mL each). Compound 1 was recovered in the 40% aq CH3CN fraction. This fraction was further puriﬁed by HPLC using a reverse-phase C18 column (PEGASIL ODS SP100, i.d. 20 × 250 mm) under the following conditions: solvent, a 50-min linear gradient from 25 to 50% aq CH3CN; ﬂow rate, 6.0 ml min−1; detection, UV at 210 nm. Under these conditions, com- pound 1 was eluted as a peak with a retention time of 35 min. This fraction was concentrated in vacuo and lyophi- lized to dryness to yield pure compound 1 (0.9 mg) as an orange solid. Compounds 2–4 were recovered in the 60% aq CH3CN fraction. The 1H NMR spectrum of 1 displayed 40 proton signals in DMSO-d6 (Supplementary Fig. S2). The connectivity of all proton and carbon atoms was established by HSQC experiments (Table 1). An ana- lysis of 1H–1H COSY spectra indicated two partial struc- tures I and II, as shown by the bold lines in Fig. 2a. The 13C NMR chemical shift values from C-1′ to C-5′ also indicated that the partial structure II belonged to a sugar moiety. Furthermore, an analysis of HMBC spectra revealed the following linkages: (1) Cross peaks were observed from H- 1 (δ 7.21) and H-11 (δ 7.87) to C-12 (δ 181.1) and from H- 11 (δ 7.87) to C-5 (δ 190.4), indicating the presence of an anthraquinone structure consisting of A, B, and C rings (Fig. 2a). The relative stereochemistry of 1 was mainly analyzed by ROESY experiments (Figs. 2b and S6). ROESY corre- lations from H-7 (δ 4.89) to H-8a (δ 2.32), and from H3−13 (δ 1.23) to H-8b (δ 1.88) and OH-10 (δ 5.64) indicated that the relative stereochemistry of the D ring was elucidated as 7 S*8 R*9 S*10 S* (Fig. 2b). Regarding the sugar moiety, observations of JH3’-4 = 10.2 Hz and JH4’-5 = 8.7 Hz and ROESY correlations from H-3’ (δ 3.35) to H-5’ (δ 3.53) indicated that H-3’, H-4’, and H-5’ were axial. H-1′ and H- 2′ were both suggested to be equatorial based on observa- tions of ROESY correlations between H-1′ and H-2′ in place of those between H-1′ and H-3′, and less coupling constants of JH1’-2’ and JH2’-3’. These results showed that the sugar moiety of 1 was 6-deoxy-2-methoxy-β-mannopyr- anose. This was reasonable because a previous study also demonstrated that stefﬁmycin has the same relative stereo- chemistry as 1 [6]. Furthermore, compounds 2–4 were identiﬁed as stefﬁmycin, 10-dihydrostefﬁmycin, and 8- demethoxystefﬁmycin, respectively, based on comparisons with previous NMR data described in the literature [4, 5, 7]. The anti-mycobacterial activities of 1–4, including M. avium and M. intracellulare, were evaluated according to a liquid microdilution method [8]. Compound 1 exhibited moderate anti-mycobacterial activity against M. intracellu- lare, M. bovis BCG, and M. smegmatis with respective MIC values of 6.25, 25.0, and 12.5 µg ml−1 (Table 2a), whereas negligible activity was observed against M. avium (MIC value: >50 µg ml−1). In contrast, compounds 2–4 had stronger potencies towards the four mycobacteria tested (Table 2a). These results indicated that the C8 and C10 positions of stefﬁmycins affect their potencies. Furthermore, the mammalian cell cytotoxicities of 1–4 were evaluated using HeLa cells according to our established method [9]. The IC50 values of 1–4 were 76.1, 47.2, 68.4, and 57.0 µg ml−1, respectively (Table 2b). Their selectivity ranged between 12.2-fold and 146.2-fold based on comparisons with activity against M. intracellulare (Table 2b). Structu- rally related daunorubicin exhibited stronger cell cytotoxi- city as well as lower selectivity towards activity against M. intracellulare (Table 2b).

In conclusion, we herein discovered one new and three known and structurally related compounds produced by the marine actinomycete strain Streptomyces sp. OPMA02852. Other groups reported that compounds 3 and 4 were obtained via the microbial conversion of stefﬁmycin by Actinoplanes sp.
